# Contract normalization responsibilities

## Overview

Contract **normalization** (hydrating JSON-clean envelopes into class-instance IR, stamping discriminators on polymorphic slots, omitting defaults during round-tripping) has a single well-defined seam: the family **`ContractSerializer`**. Every read of an on-disk contract crosses this seam; every in-memory authoring path enters the IR through a constructor that enforces the same shape.

This rule replaces an earlier version that asserted normalization was the contract builder's job alone and that the validator was strictly structure-only. That stance reflected a pre-serializer-seam world. With the SQL family `ContractSerializer` in place (TML-2536), the validator both **validates** (arktype-structural) **and** **hydrates** (constructs IR-class instances) — those operations are inseparable and live behind a single named entry point.

## The seam: `familyInstance.validateContract`

```text
on-disk JSON
   │
   │  JSON.parse(raw) as unknown   ← every CLI on-disk read does this much
   │
   ▼
familyInstance.validateContract(json)            ← THE seam
   │
   ▼
target.contractSerializer.deserializeContract(json)
   │
   ├── parseSqlContractStructure(json)           ← arktype structural validation
   │       └── validateSqlContractFully(...)
   │              └── StorageTypeEntrySchema enforces `kind` discriminators
   │                  on polymorphic `storage.types` entries
   │
   ├── hydrateSqlStorage(validated)              ← IR-class construction
   │       └── new SqlStorage({...})
   │              ├── new StorageTable(...)      ← cascading constructors
   │              ├── new StorageColumn(...)
   │              ├── new PrimaryKey(...), ...
   │              └── normaliseTypeEntry(name, entry)
   │                     ├── PostgresEnumType    (kind: 'postgres-enum')
   │                     └── StorageTypeInstance (kind: 'codec-instance')
   │                     └── THROW if discriminator unrecognised
   │
   └── constructTargetContract(hydrated)         ← target hook
           (Postgres returns identity today;
            target-only derived fields would attach here)
```

Code: `packages/2-sql/9-family/src/core/control-instance.ts`, `packages/2-sql/9-family/src/core/ir/sql-contract-serializer-base.ts`, `packages/3-targets/3-targets/postgres/src/core/postgres-contract-serializer.ts`, `packages/2-sql/1-core/contract/src/ir/sql-storage.ts`.

## Responsibilities

### Family `ContractSerializer` — the only normalization seam

- Calls into `parseSqlContractStructure` (arktype) — every required field present, every discriminator recognised, every polymorphic slot entry tagged.
- Hydrates the validated envelope through `hydrateSqlStorage` and per-entity hydration factories registered by the target pack (Postgres registers `postgres-enum` → `PostgresEnumType`).
- Returns a fully-hydrated `Contract` whose `storage` is a `SqlStorage` instance, its `tables`/columns/keys/etc. are IR-class instances, and its polymorphic `types` entries are tagged-and-typed.

### Validator — validates **and** hydrates (no longer "structure-only")

The arktype schemas in `packages/2-sql/1-core/contract/src/validators.ts` reject malformed envelopes; the surrounding `SqlContractSerializerBase.deserializeContract` hydrates them into IR-class instances. These two steps are not separable — there is no public API for "just validate, don't hydrate".

### Contract builder / PSL interpreter — authors the canonical shape

The TypeScript contract builder (`packages/2-sql/2-authoring/contract-ts/src/build-contract.ts`) and the PSL interpreter (`packages/2-sql/2-authoring/contract-psl/src/interpreter.ts`) produce contracts directly in the canonical shape — every `storage.types[*]` entry carries its `kind` discriminator at authoring time; `toStorageTypeInstance(...)` is used wherever a raw codec triple needs the `kind: 'codec-instance'` discriminator stamped.

### CLI on-disk reads — must route through the seam

Every command that reads a `contract.json` (or `end-contract.json`, `start-contract.json`) from disk crosses the seam:

```typescript
// ✅ CORRECT
const raw = await readFile(path, 'utf-8');
const contract = familyInstance.validateContract(JSON.parse(raw) as unknown);
```

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG — see the as-contract-cast-smell rule
const contract = JSON.parse(raw) as Contract;
```

A workspace lint (`pnpm lint:no-contract-cast`) fails on the wrong pattern in `packages/**/src/**`.

### In-memory IR construction — same strict shape

`new SqlStorage({...})` is the only path that creates the live IR. Its constructor enforces the same `storage.types` discriminator rules as the deserializer: untagged entries throw a diagnostic that names the offending slot key. Authoring code that has a raw codec triple on hand wraps it with `toStorageTypeInstance(...)` before construction.

## What this means for callers

- **Reading a contract from disk?** Call `familyInstance.validateContract(JSON.parse(raw) as unknown)`. Never cast `JSON.parse(...) as Contract` — that bypasses the seam silently.
- **Constructing a contract in memory?** Use the builder or instantiate `SqlStorage` directly with explicitly-tagged `storage.types` entries.
- **Writing a contract back to disk?** Use `target.contractSerializer.serializeContract(contract)` (the default is identity over JSON-clean class instances; targets override when they ship runtime-only fields that must not appear in the JSON envelope).

